# Export user guide sync

The end-user doc is **`docs/DATA-GOVERNANCE/Cortex Export - User Guide.md`**. When **export-all** behavior, layout, or semantics change, update that guide in the **same change**—do not leave it stale.

## When to update

Update the guide when a change affects anything a reader or LLM consumer would notice:

- Markdown **section numbers, titles, or boundaries** (§1–§7, §3b / §3b-renewal / §3b-future, etc.)
- **What is included or excluded** per section (Pendo, Jira, Salesforce segments, CS Report, Slack, risk insights)
- **Customer status** vocabulary (`commercial_status`, current book vs churn / renewal / future)
- **ARR fields** or how customers are **ranked / capped** (top-N, env vars, ultimate-parent grouping)
- **CLI flags**, default lookback, Drive output filename/path, size caps, or filters (`--customers-sf-allowlist`, etc.)
- **Coverage / omission** messaging at the top of the export
- New **example prompts** when a section is added or its purpose shifts materially

## What to skip

- Internal refactors with no user-visible export change
- Test-only or fixture tweaks that do not change export content
- Technical catalog paths — those belong in `DATA_DICTIONARY.md`, not the user guide

## How to update

- Write for **non-technical readers** (CS, AMs, leadership): plain English, short tables, example AI prompts where helpful
- Keep operator/CLI details in a brief **“For operators”** section at the end
- If the guide is renamed, update links in `docs/DATA-GOVERNANCE/README.md` and `DATA_DICTIONARY.md` in the same change

## Completion check

Before marking export-all work done, confirm the user guide still matches the snapshot: section map, status/ARR rules, caps, and at least one prompt example for any new section.
